: ''For the [[Japanese era name|Japanese era]], see [[Keian]] (1648-1652).'' [[File:Keian Genju.jpg|thumb|right|Keian Genju at Kagoshima]] [[File:Tomb of Keian Genju.jpg|thumb|right|Tomb of Keian Genju in Kagoshima]]
{{nihongo|'''Keian Genju'''|桂庵 玄樹||1427 – June 28, 1508}} was a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] monk <ref>Ponsonby-Fane, Richard. (1962). ''Sovereign and Subject,'' p. 242-246.</ref><ref>Iwao, Seiichi ''et al.'' (2002). [https://books.google.com/books?id=NBlDYE38ODYC&pg=PA1490&dq= ''Dictionnaire historique du Japon'' (Vol. I)], p. 1490.</ref> who studied classics under [[Ishō]] at [[Nanzen-ji]].<ref>Ponsonby-Fane, p. 243.</ref>
Keian accompanied the 1466 [[Japanese missions to Ming China|mission to the Ming court in China]]. In [[Beijing]], he was favored by the [[Chenghua Emperor]].<ref name="ponsonby244">Ponsonby-Fane, p. 244.</ref> Keian delayed his return to Japan until 1475.<ref name="ponsonby244"/>
Keian was the first to translate [[Zhu Xi]]'s ''Collective Commentaries on the Great Learning'' into Japanese.<ref>Xinzhong Yao. (2005). [https://books.google.com/books?id=tAE2OJ9bPG0C&pg=PA127&lpg=PA127&dq= ''An Introduction to Confucianism,'' p. 127.]</ref>
Keian founded Satsunan-gakuha, a neo-confucianist school in Kagoshima.<ref>Iwao, Seiichi ''et al.'' (2002). [https://books.google.com/books?id=NBlDYE38ODYC&pg=PA1490&dq=keian+1427-1508+seiichi+iwao&ei=nDDZSu2bGYG0yQSv3-nVDg&client=firefox-a#v=onepage&q=&f=false ''Dictionnaire historique du Japon'' (Vol. II)], p. 2376.</ref>
